    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-07T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-07T18:00:00-05:00" n="54"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d54">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/565</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-07T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 7, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6796. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 175. Embassy’s No. 8891, your No, 223, March 4, 9 p.m. We approve of your
                    suggestion as to modifying paragraph 3 of our 113. If this method of handling
                    applications to import in northern European neutrals is finally agreed to in
                    London, please inform our Legations in Holland, Norway, Sweden, and Denmark, and
                    advise us that you have done so. It was our intention and we still feel that
                    considerable latitude should be left the local joint committees in developing
                    the most efficacious method of handling import applications, and that probably
                    different methods would have to be adopted in the different countries.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
